# TypeScript Rules

This rule defines the TypeScript conventions for the project.

Goals:

- Strong type safety
- Predictable architecture
- Readable code
- Minimal runtime overhead

These rules apply to all TypeScript files.

---

## 1) Avoid `any`

Never use `any`. Prefer `unknown`, generics, proper interfaces, or discriminated unions. This includes implicit `any` in callbacks — always type parameters explicitly or let TypeScript infer from context.

```ts
// Good
const parse = (data: unknown) => {
	if (typeof data === 'string') return data;
};

const numbers: number[] = [1, 2, 3];
numbers.map(num => num * 2);

// Avoid
const parse = (data: any) => data;

const numbers = [];
numbers.map(num => num * 2); // num is implicitly any
```

Reason: `any` disables TypeScript safety, including in callback parameters.

---

## 2) Prefer Explicit React Function Components

Do not use `React.FC`. Use explicit function components with typed props.

```ts
// Good
interface Props { title: string }
const Card = (props: Props) => <div>{props.title}</div>;

// Avoid
const Card: React.FC<Props> = ({ title }) => <div>{title}</div>;
```

Reason: `React.FC` implicitly includes `children` and hides component API.

---

## 3) Prefer `as const` + Union Types Instead of `enum`

Avoid TypeScript `enum`. Use `as const` on all constant objects and arrays to preserve literal types.

```ts
// Good — object
export const Paths = {
	HOME: '/',
	LOGIN: '/login',
	PROFILE: '/profile',
} as const;
export type Path = (typeof Paths)[keyof typeof Paths];

// Good — array
const STATUS = ['idle', 'loading', 'success', 'error'] as const;
type Status = (typeof STATUS)[number];

// Avoid
enum Paths {
	HOME = '/',
	LOGIN = '/login',
	PROFILE = '/profile',
}
const STATUS = ['idle', 'loading', 'success', 'error']; // widens to string[]
```

Reason: `enum` produces runtime code and harms tree-shaking. `as const` preserves literal types like `"idle"` instead of widening to `string`, improving autocomplete and type safety.

---

## 4) Interface vs Type

Use `interface` for object structures. Use `type` for unions, intersections, and compositions.

```ts
interface User {
	id: string;
	name: string;
}

type UserWithRole = User & { role: 'admin' | 'user' };
type Status = 'idle' | 'loading' | 'success';
```

Reason: `interface` is better suited for object contracts, while `type` excels at composition and unions.

---

## 5) Prefer Named Types Instead of Inline Types

Avoid large inline object types. Named types improve readability and reuse.

```ts
// Good
interface Props {
	user: User;
	isAdmin: boolean;
}

// Avoid
const Component = (props: { user: { id: string; name: string }; isAdmin: boolean }) => {};
```

---

## 6) Prefer Explicit Return Types for Shared Functions

Exported utilities should define return types to prevent accidental API changes.

```ts
const getUserName = (user: User): string => user.name;
```

---

## 7) Prefer Discriminated Unions for State

Use discriminated unions for state machines. Enables exhaustive checking and prevents impossible states.

```ts
type RequestState =
	| { status: 'idle' }
	| { status: 'loading' }
	| { status: 'success'; data: User }
	| { status: 'error'; message: string };
```

---

## 8) Avoid Magic Strings

```ts
export const USER_ROLE = { ADMIN: 'admin', USER: 'user' } as const;
export type UserRole = (typeof USER_ROLE)[keyof typeof USER_ROLE];
```

---

## 9) Prefer `readonly` for Immutable Data

Prevents accidental mutation.

```ts
interface Config { readonly apiUrl: string }
// Arrays:
readonly string[]
```

---

## 10) Prefer Generics Over Duplication

```ts
const identity = <T>(value: T): T => value;
```

Reason: Avoids duplicated logic while maintaining type safety.

---

## 11) Prefer TypeScript Utility Types

Use built-in utilities: `Partial<T>`, `Pick<T>`, `Omit<T>`, `Record<K,V>`, `ReturnType<T>`, `Parameters<T>`

```ts
type UserPreview = Pick<User, 'id' | 'name'>;
```

---

## 12) Avoid Deep Nested Types

Break nested types into separate interfaces for readability.

```ts
interface Address {
	city: string;
	zip: string;
}
interface User {
	id: string;
	address: Address;
}
```

---

## 13) Prefer Narrow Types Over Broad Types

```ts
// Good
type Theme = 'light' | 'dark';
// Avoid
type Theme = string;
```

Reason: Improves autocomplete and safety.

---

## 14) Avoid Boolean Prop Explosion

```tsx
// Avoid
<Button isPrimary isDanger />;

// Prefer
type ButtonVariant = 'primary' | 'danger';
<Button variant="primary" />;
```

Reason: Boolean flags create invalid state combinations.

---

## 15) Prefer Object Parameters (RORO Pattern)

```ts
const createUser = (params: { name: string; age: number }) => ({
	id: crypto.randomUUID(),
	...params,
});
```

Reason: Improves readability and extensibility.

---

## 16) Use `import type` for Type Imports

```ts
import type { User } from '@/types';
```

Reason: Prevents unnecessary runtime imports.

---

## 17) Prefer Exhaustive Checks With `never`

```ts
const handleState = (state: RequestState) => {
	switch (state.status) {
		case 'idle':
			return;
		case 'loading':
			return;
		case 'success':
			return state.data;
		case 'error':
			throw new Error(state.message);
		default:
			const _exhaustive: never = state;
			return _exhaustive;
	}
};
```

Reason: Ensures all cases are handled.

---

## 18) Keep Types Close to Their Domain

Types should be organized in the `src/modules/types/` directory.

Use PascalCase file names matching the type name (singular form). Each file exports related types and interfaces.

```
src/modules/types/
  User.ts
  Organization.ts
  Member.ts
  ResourceType.ts
  Reservations.ts
```

Use `import type` when importing types from these files:

```ts
import type { User } from '@/modules/types/User';
import type { Organization, OrganizationLike } from '@/modules/types/Organization';
```

Reason: Centralized type definitions improve discoverability and maintainability. Consistent naming makes types easy to locate.

---

## 19) Avoid Unsafe Type Assertions

Avoid `as` type assertions whenever possible. Prefer type guards and safe narrowing instead.

```ts
// Good
const parseUser = (data: unknown): User | null => {
	if (typeof data === 'object' && data !== null && 'id' in data) {
		return data as User;
	}
	return null;
};

// Avoid
const user = data as User;
```

Reason: `as` bypasses TypeScript's type checker and can cause runtime errors. Always narrow types safely through the type system.

---

## 20) Prefer Type Guards When Handling `unknown`

Use type predicates to narrow `unknown` safely and reuse the check across the codebase.

```ts
// Good
const isUser = (data: unknown): data is User => {
	return typeof data === 'object' && data !== null && 'id' in data;
};

// Avoid
const user = data as User;
```

Reason: type guards make narrowing explicit, reusable, and safe — unlike `as` which silently bypasses the type checker.

---

## 21) Prefer `satisfies` for Object Type Validation

Use `satisfies` when you want to validate an object's shape while preserving its literal types.

```ts
// Good
const routes = {
	home: '/',
	login: '/login',
} as const satisfies Record<string, string>;

// Avoid
const routes: Record<string, string> = {
	home: '/',
	login: '/login',
}; // loses literal types — routes.home is string, not '/'
```

Reason: `satisfies` validates structure at compile time without widening literal types, giving you both safety and autocomplete.
